I guess I would like to have him tell me much more about his mother and father and growing up out there.

41:28.173 --> 41:30.616
And what were these formative years like?

41:31.477 --> 41:37.125
If the mother was in fact illiterate, as you believe she was, do you think this in any way impacted the way he developed?

41:37.345 --> 41:46.056
Maybe he wanted, maybe it was so, you say he went to Harvard, discovered books and read for... Well, there's a passage in my book, which is from a letter of his,

41:46.542 --> 41:58.882
where I think he saw in his mother some of his own eccentricities, his capacity to flare up, lose his temper, and so forth.

41:59.743 --> 42:03.810
And then she sees that he really isn't cut out to be a preacher, a minister.

42:04.511 --> 42:13.866
So my guess is that he saw a lot of himself in her, some of which he may not have liked, but I think he also knew that she understood him.

42:15.888 --> 42:21.013
There has been a theory that he didn't like her because there are no letters to her.

42:21.314 --> 42:22.315
Well, she can't read.

42:22.355 --> 42:25.778
That's pretty obvious, yeah.

42:25.798 --> 42:28.821
You know, if you get that.

42:28.841 --> 42:31.544
I mean, Alexander the Great wrote to his mother they could both read.

42:31.564 --> 42:32.785
They're very simple things.

42:32.805 --> 42:42.655
You know, the visitors to the encamped soldiers around Boston during the siege of Boston, both Americans and the Brits, are astounded how dirty these men are.

42:43.356 --> 42:45.338
Well, they're dirty because they're out digging

42:45.537 --> 42:49.584
trenches and making breastworks and fortifications all day long.

42:50.084 --> 42:53.150
They're dirty because they're working in the dirt with their hands.

42:53.230 --> 42:56.615
And you have to understand the reality.

42:57.076 --> 42:59.059
Would you do my wife and myself?

42:59.079 --> 43:00.041
Oh, I sure will.

43:01.022 --> 43:04.869
Connie, and she, if anyone can claim to be... And what is her name?

43:05.009 --> 43:06.351
Connie, C-O-N-N-I-E.

43:07.193 --> 43:12.321
If anyone can claim to be more than me to be your greatest fan, it's my wife, I have to say.

43:14.647 --> 43:16.429
This is on tape, because this is important for me.

43:18.191 --> 43:19.993
This is the fourth interview you and I have had.

43:20.013 --> 43:39.675
I remember them, of course, but our first one, before I was even a book editor, was when Path Between the Seas came out on the telephone, and then I came to visit you at your home, you graciously, and I saw that old iron side, the .44 guns in your wall, and I went out and got three copies of that, and I had one of my father-in-law's houses, and my father-in-law's houses.

43:40.263 --> 43:50.333
So that was the 70s, and then we spoke again in the 80s on Teddy Roosevelt, and then we spoke in the 90s on Harry Truman, and here we are in the fourth decade talking about other things.

43:50.453 --> 43:55.537
And so I think of the many, many, many interviews I've done with authors over the years.

43:56.659 --> 43:57.079
Thank you.

43:57.199 --> 44:03.845
You're the first one to spend four decades, and every decade, and by far the best for me.

44:04.246 --> 44:08.169
And a model for what I try to do in my own work, may I say.

44:08.470 --> 44:09.831
Thank you very much.

44:10.098 --> 44:10.599
Thank you.

44:10.940 --> 44:15.912
If I can even approach what you do as a writer of narrative nonfiction.

44:15.932 --> 44:24.293
You do wonderful work in book publishing and authorship in your work.

44:25.117 --> 44:27.641
And if you don't mind, just a little one on that.

44:27.661 --> 44:29.544
This is a gem, I have to say.

44:30.104 --> 44:30.605
Thank you.

44:30.625 --> 44:32.388
I've had nice... You can see I've handled it.

44:32.408 --> 44:33.149
I apologize.

44:33.269 --> 44:35.472
All these notes in here, by the way, are my wife.

44:35.532 --> 44:38.497
